  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "A large pen drawing (420 x 287 mm) in brown and red ink on paper, attributed to **David Jorisz.** (c. 1501–1556), depicting an allegorical scene in which a figure representing David (identifiable by a poet's wreath, a lyre at his feet, and a sling) battles three chained allegorical figures: Power (holding a globe), Violence (a soldier), and the Body/Flesh (a woman). A skull emphasizes their defeat. Through an arched gateway dated **1536** in the composition, a modern-dressed figure receives scales from heaven — symbolizing spiritual liberation through divine love. The composition is understood as both a biblical illustration and an indirect **self-portrait of David Joris** as the prophetic \"third David\" following his December 1536 visions. Acquired at Christie's Paris, 18 May 2022 (lot 22, sold for **€126,000**) with support from the Vereniging Rembrandt. Designated one of Teylers' **50 Topstukken**. First confirmed drawing by David Joris in any Dutch public collection.",
